article.headline: Celtics snap road skid by topping Clippers
article.linkText: Celtics snap road skid by topping Clippers
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Boston Celtics were happy to end their six-game road losing streak. Ricky Davis scored 20 points, Paul Pierce added 19 and four of their teammates also reached double digits in Boston's 111-92 victory over the Clippers on Saturday night. "We wanted to finish the year off right," Pierce said. "We know we've been so close, and for us to get a win like this feels good -- especially finishing 2005 off with a win. But we've won back-to-back games once this year, so I don't think we're going to get too high. I mean, we're still trying to build some consistency as a team. Hopefully, we got the monkey off our back." Cuttino Mobley scored 27 points and Sam Cassell had 24 for the Clippers, who lost for the seventh time in nine games. They have dropped 10 of their last 12 against Boston, including a double-overtime defeat last season at Staples Center. The Celtics, who overcame a 20-point deficit to beat the Clippers the last time they faced each other last February in Boston, enjoyed a 20-point lead in the second quarter of the rematch. Los Angeles rallied as both Cassell and Mobley had 12 points in the third quarter to pull the Clippers within 89-76. Mobley's 3-pointer cut Boston's lead to 91-81 with 9 minutes to play, but the Clippers got no closer. The Celtics answered with a 15-2 run capped by consecutive jumpers by Pierce, a 19-footer by Davis and a 3-pointer by Delonte West to pull out to a commanding 103-83 lead with 3:22 remaining. "They made shots," said Cassell, who left the game with 3:12 remaining after tweaking his left ankle but was expected to play on Sunday at Portland. "They've got two great players in Ricky and Paul who can shoot off the dribble, so nothing they did tonight really surprises me." After totaling 45 turnovers over their previous two games, Boston had only three before halftime and finished with 14. "We passed the ball pretty well and kept our turnovers down," Pierce said. "A lot of guys were big tonight and were able to step up. Rafe (LaFrentz) was big for us, Marcus (Banks) really gave us a lift early, and that's what got us going." The Clippers scored the game's first eight points, but the Celtics took the lead for good by scoring the first eight points of the second period to break a 31-all tie. Los Angeles coach Mike Dunleavy extended his bench because of injuries to Corey Maggette and Quinton Ross. But the energized Celtics, coming off a 116-112 loss at Sacramento on Friday, were no match for the sluggish Clippers in the fourth game of their five-game road trip. Four players reached double figures for Boston in the first half, helping build a 64-56 lead. It was the most points scored in a half by the Celtics this season, and the most given up by the Clippers in a half. "We started pretty well, but then we hit that second-quarter lull," said Elton Brand, who finished with just 11 points on 5-for-16 shooting and had five rebounds. "We didn't play any defense and they got layup after layup." Boston opened up a 60-40 cushion with an 18-5 run capped by a breakaway slam dunk by Davis that left Cassell and Mobley in his wake with 2:06 left in the second quarter. Three of the last four baskets in that rally came off defensive rebounds by Mark Blount. "The key was just stopping their key guys and making it tough for E.B. on the post," Davis said. "We've been playing great lately. Now that we're on the west coast, I think we've been moving it up and down the court a little more and getting out and running. We're also doing a lot of random stuff like pick-and-rolls, and that kind of hurt them." Clippers reserve forward Walter McCarty, who spent seven-plus seasons with the Celtics before getting traded to Phoenix last February, played 10 minutes without scoring.

Game notes
The Clippers are 16-12 -- the best winning percentage they've taken into New Year's Day in the last 30 years. ... The Celtics, who shot 56.6 percent from the field, are 2-7 when shooting over 50 percent and 1-6 on the road. ... West played an entire game without a turnover for the fifth time this season and has just seven over his last nine games. ... Michael Smith, who was chosen 13th overall by the Celtics in the 1989 draft out of Brigham Young, is in his eighth season as a Clippers broadcaster and fourth as their TV analyst after four seasons of radio play-by-play.
